This paper deals with anomaly detection in distributed cyber-physical systems (CPSs) using a data-driven framework based on spatiotemporal feature extraction and Restricted Boltzmann Machine (RBM) learning. The paper involves concepts from system modeling, machine learning, and cybersecurity, which are relevant to several sub-categories of computer science. However, given the focus on CPSs and system-wide anomaly detection, the most likely sub-category is cs.SY (Systems and Control). The paper also involves unsupervised learning and graphical modeling, which are relevant to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper deals with cybersecurity and fault detection, which are relevant to cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
